[2]
Date: Mon 24 Feb 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Ultima Hora (Paraguay), Sat 22 Feb 2003 [translated by Maria
Jacobs, ProMED-ESP] [edited]
<http://www.ultimahora.com/template.asp?notic=26683>

Paraguay: Dengue Virus Serotype 3 - Alert
-----------------------------------------
The confirmation of circulation of dengue virus serotype 3 in the
community of Pedro Juan Caballero has placed Paraguay under a state
of alert. The more than 600 000 people who already had a dengue
serotype 1 infection run the risk of developing hemorrhagic
manifestations in case of a second infection by a different serotype.
10 cases of dengue serotype 3 were confirmed in the Bernardino
Caballero district of Pedro Juan Caballero. None have presented
hemorrhagic manifestations of the disease, but there are another 2000
people in this city at risk of acquiring dengue hemorrhagic fever
[DHF] if they become infected again.
The Ministry of Health has declared an epidemiological alert in the
whole country. Jose Antonio Mayans, Minister of Health, stated that
it is a very serious situation and that, while the intention is not
to alarm the population, it is necessary to take every responsible
measure when addressing these cases. The Ministry's greatest concern
lies in the inability of hospitals to deal with severe cases should
there be an epidemic. In a worst-case scenario, if dengue virus
serotype 3 disseminates, and the 600 000 susceptible Paraguayans
become reinfected, 10 percent (around 60 000 people) could develop
the hemorrhagic form of the disease, and of these, 10 percent would
be very serious, life-threatening cases.
In addition, DHF could be very costly to the public health system.
While the cost of treatment of classic dengue fever is approximately
400 000 guarani [approximately US $58], including laboratory tests,
the cost of the treatment of DHF could exceed 7 million guarani
[around US $1000]. A DHF patient does not require intensive care but
does require around-the-clock physician care during the acute stage
of the disease. It is evident that the Public Health Ministry, with
its scarce resources, is in no condition to face an epidemic.
As a preventive measure, Senepa [National Service for the Eradication
of Malaria] is attempting to contain risk within the high-risk area,
and last Thursday fumigated 106 blocks in the districts of Maria
Victoria, Bernardino Caballero, and Guarani. However, on Friday, the
rain reduced the effectiveness of the pesticide treatment.
Health authorities are urging all people with fever to visit a
physician so that they may detect suspected cases and restrict
movement to and from the affected area. The Central Laboratory offers
blood tests for dengue fever at no cost. Authorities are also urging
residents to organize groups to clean houses, public ways, and
abandoned lots. Some communities have designated days when employees
can be absent from work and participate in the cleaning project.
Carlos Romero, Director of Senepa, has complained that the
municipality of Asuncion, where the index of mosquito infestation is
80 percent, is not cooperating.
Since 1989, Paraguay has reported epidemic outbreaks of dengue fever
type 1 or classic dengue fever, mostly in Asuncion and in communities
along the borders with Argentina and Brazil, but no deaths have been
reported. An outbreak of dengue fever is currently affecting several
Brazilian and Argentine cities close to the border with Paraguay, as
well as the Bolivian city of Santa Cruz, where more than 300
confirmed cases and 2 deaths have been registered. The provinces of
Salta and Misiones in Argentina have reported more than 260 cases,
and Foz de Iguazu in Brazil has reported 21 cases.
Romero, a member of a multidisciplinary committee created to combat
the disease, stated that the situation is critical, and that efforts
must be redoubled, since recent rains in the whole country could
cause a 30 percent increase in the index of mosquito infestation. He
asked the population to collaborate in the elimination of mosquito
breeding sites, warning that a repeat infection by the new serotype
could develop into the hemorrhagic form of the disease, requiring
hospitalization, and that an epidemic could overwhelm the health
system.
--
