[7]
Date: Mon 3 Mar 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Arab News, Mon 3 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://www.arabnews.com/Article.asp?ID=23271>

Saudi Arabia: Alkhurma Virus Implicated as Etiologic Agent
--------------------------------------------------
The discovery of 7 cases of dengue fever here has raised concern
among the general public. They are complaining that they are not
being provided enough information about the disease, which caused an
epidemic in the Kingdom in 1994. 4 of the 7 cases of dengue fever in
Jeddah were treated at the Al-Fakeeh Hospital, and all of the
individuals have fully recovered, Dr. Ali Zaki of the Virology
Laboratory at Al-Fakeeh Hospital in Jeddah told Arab News yesterday.
Dr. Zaki isolated the dengue virus in 1994, and also has among his
credits being the first person to discover the Alkhurma strain of the
virus.
People living in the Faisaliya and Bawadi districts of Jeddah are
apparently most at risk at present, since the districts are the main
centers of infected mosquito activity. But conditions in the city
generally are ripe for the disease to spread. Jeddah is full of pools
of stagnant water, overflowing septic tanks, a rising water table
coming up through holes in pavements and on waste ground, leaking
sewage tankers, leaking water pipes, and inadequate -- if not
non-existent -- drainage.
"Today it is much easier to detect dengue in the Kingdom than it was
in 1994, because we now have a ready-made kit especially designed for
that purpose, and if patients come to us within 4 days of being
infected, they recover much faster," Dr. Zaki said. The Alkhurma
strain of the virus was detected by Dr. Zaki in 1994 and named after
the Saudi town of Alkhurma.
The Alkhurma virus (ALKV) is a tick-borne flavivirus responsible for
hemorrhagic fever in humans. The first symptoms include vomiting,
epigastric pain, diarrhea, and hematemesis for more than 4 days. The
patient also suffers from an elevated liver enzyme, Dr. Zaki told
Arab News. Dr. Zaki explained that all the Alkhurma patients had a
history of direct contact with animals and meat.
The main difference between dengue virus and the Alkhurma strain is
that dengue is spread by mosquitoes, while Alkhurma can be caught
through direct contact with animals and fresh meat, and is spread
only by ticks. The first 6 patients were actually butchers. The
fatality rate of the Alkhurma virus is much higher than that of
dengue; 2 of the 16 cases so far discovered have been fatal, compared
with only one in every 1000 for dengue.
Trial vaccines are now being tested, Zaki said, but the disease is
not 100 percent curable. The only solution is to control the
mosquitoes and avoid direct contact with animals.
[Byline: Sarah Abuljadayel]
[This second report implicates Alkhurma virus (a tick-borne
flavivirus) as the causative agent, rather than the mosquito-borne
dengue virus; both viruses occur in Saudi Arabia. It is incorrect to
state that Alkhurma virus is a "strain" of dengue virus. Alkhurma
virus is a distinct virus species responsible for a distinctive
disease syndrome. Alkhurma virus belongs to the tick-borne group of
flaviviruses, which also includes Omsk hemorrhagic fever virus
(isolated in Siberia) and Kyasanur Forest disease virus (isolated in
India). Analysis of structural genes, genetic distances, and
evolutionary relationship indicate that Alkhurma virus and Kyasanur
Forest disease virus are derived from a common phylogenetic ancestor
and constitute 2 genetic subtypes of the same virus species according
to current genetic criteria of classification. (See Charrel, R.M., et
al. Biochem Biophys Res Commun 2001 Sep 21;287(2):455-61). Further
information on the current prevalence of both Alkhurma virus and
dengue virus in humans and animals in Saudi Arabia would be
appreciated. - Mod.CP]
